<h2>Resize an Image on Windows</h2>

<p>If you prefer desktop methods:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Paint:</strong> Open → Resize (Home tab) → set pixels → save. Simple, but no aspect ratio locking.</li>
  <li><strong>Photos app:</strong> Open → three-dot menu → Resize → choose a preset or enter custom dimensions.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Resize an Image on Mac</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the image in <strong>Preview</strong>.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Tools → Adjust Size</strong>.</li>
  <li>Enter width or height. Tick "Scale proportionally" to lock aspect ratio.</li>
  <li>Click OK and save.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Resize on iPhone or Android</h2>

<p>
  The browser-based Image Resizer works on mobile too — open it in Chrome or Safari, upload your image, and download the resized version directly to your phone's camera roll.
</p>

<h2>Tips for Best Results</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Always resize from the original high-resolution file, not from a copy that's already been compressed.</li>
  <li>For web images, save as JPEG at 85–90% quality for the best size-to-quality ratio.</li>
  <li>For images that need transparency (logos, icons), save as PNG.</li>
  <li>WebP gives the best compression for web use and is supported in all modern browsers.</li>
</ul>

